      A certain amount of crime
   =20
 =20

Finance rewards cleverness. Sometimes this is true in a pleasingly positive=
-sum way; if you can cleverly think up a new way to slice cash flows or all=
ocate risk then you can get rich by increasing economic activity. Often, th=
ough, it is true in some straightforwardly zero-sum way: If you have a cont=
ract with a counterparty, and you cleverly ferret out a hidden provision in=
 the contract that says that your counterparty has to give you $10 million,=
 then you get $10 million and they lose $10 million.=C2=A0
We talk quite a lot around here about those stories. Lots of market structu=
re, for instance, falls into this category: If you find a way to buy stock =
a bit before someone else does, you win and they lose, but not necessarily =
in a way that makes the world better. It=E2=80=99s just a game that you=E2=
=80=99re playing with each other. Or: People finding clever readings of cre=
dit-default swaps=20
was a=20
big theme of this=20
column for a few=20
years. Someone buys CDS to bet against (or hedge) the credit risk of a comp=
any, and someone else sells them that CDS to bet on the credit of that comp=
any, and then the buyer and the seller separately go to the company and say=
 =E2=80=9Chey if you press this button right here our counterparty will hav=
e to give us $50 million and we=E2=80=99ll give you $20 million of it,=E2=
=80=9D and the company is like =E2=80=9Cwho are you? Sure, I guess,=E2=80=
=9D and it is=C2=A0weird. There are intersections between this stuff and th=
e real economic world =E2=80=94=C2=A0I think that sometimes it is net good=
=C2=A0for the world, and other times it is net=C2=A0bad=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it mostly feels pretty abstract. Some hedge funds are trying to tric=
k each other using finance and that=E2=80=99s just their business.
There are, in the traditional financial system,=C2=A0constraints=C2=A0on th=
is sort of cleverness. Obviously one set of constraints is, like, it is har=
d to find arbitrages in markets or flaws in contracts, and the people on th=
e other side are also smart and have good computers and good lawyers and ar=
e trying to trick you too. Still, sometimes you will find a winning trade.
Even so, though,   there are a lot of external constraints, constraints of =
laws and norms. If you find a flaw in a contract that says your counterpart=
y has to pay you $50 million, she might say no. And you might go to court o=
ver it, and point to the language that says she has to pay you $50 million,=
 and the judge might say =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, this is stupid, it can=E2=80=99=
t have=C2=A0meant=C2=A0that, get out of here.=E2=80=9D The judge will refer=
 to vague ideas =E2=80=94=C2=A0equity, the intent of the parties, the coven=
ant of good faith and fair dealing =E2=80=94=C2=A0to reject your clever rea=
ding of the contract.=C2=A0And then you won=E2=80=99t get your $50 million.=
 There is some amount of cleverness that is=C2=A0too clever.
Or if you find some really clever market-structure trick, some button that =
you can push to reliably make money on every trade, a regulator might=C2=A0=
show up and accuse you of =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulation.=E2=80=9D That is a =
somewhat ill-defined concept, but if you are reliably making money on every=
 trade by being cleverer than your counterparties, there=E2=80=99s a decent=
 chance that you are guilty of it. (And in=C2=A0fact the US Securities and =
Exchange Commission   seems to think that causing a =E2=80=9Cmanufactured d=
efault=E2=80=9D in CDS =E2=80=94=C2=A0asking a company to push a button=C2=
=A0to make your CDS counterparty pay you =E2=80=94=C2=A0is illegal market m=
anipulation.)
Or: About a decade ago, some electricity traders at JPMorgan Chase & Co. re=
ad the rule book of the electricity market really closely and  noticed that=
 the rules would reward them for insanely uneconomic activity. They did thi=
s insanely uneconomic activity, and were richly rewarded. And then they wer=
e even more richly fined by regulators. I once   wrote about this case:
JPMorgan read the rules carefully and greedily, and exploited the rules. It=
 did this openly and honestly, in ways that were ridiculous but=C2=A0explic=
itly allowed by the rules. The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission fined i=
t $410 million for doing this, and JPMorgan meekly paid up. What JPMorgan d=
id was explicitly=C2=A0allowed by the rules, but that doesn't mean that it =
was=C2=A0allowed. Just because rules are dumb and you are smart, that doesn=
't always mean that you get to take advantage of them.
At some very high level of generality, there are the explicit rules =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the words of the contract, the mechanisms of the stock exchange, e=
tc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then there is a background set of fairness norms. An=
d if you find a way to make a ton of money with a too-clever reading of the=
 explicit rules, the background fairness norms will kick into gear and you =
will get in trouble. Following the rules is good, but following the rules t=
o absurd places is bad, perhaps a crime.
In crypto =E2=80=A6=C2=A0yeesh. In crypto, explicit rules are very popular,=
 and are often coded into computer programs. The rules of a decentralized f=
inance market will be embedded in open-source smart contracts, and you can =
read them, and if you find a clever way to exploit them =E2=80=94=C2=A0to =
=E2=80=9Chack=E2=80=9D the smart contract, or to =E2=80=9Cmanipulate=E2=80=
=9D the market, to use loaded, traditional terms =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you ca=
n do that, quickly and efficiently and at scale.
But crypto is also very=C2=A0young, as an industry, which means two things:
=09All these smart contracts were written 20 minutes ago, they do not have =
many years of testing, and some of them will have big flaws that someone ca=
n exploit.=09There is not long-standing agreement on some set of background=
 norms about what to do when that happens.

And so sometimes there will be a =E2=80=9Chack=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cexploit=
=E2=80=9D in crypto and people will say =E2=80=9Chey that=E2=80=99s great, =
the contract worked as written, you=E2=80=99re not allowed to complain.=E2=
=80=9D (Thus the scare quotes around =E2=80=9Chack=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cex=
ploit=E2=80=9D: Some people will deny that those loaded=C2=A0terms apply.)=
=C2=A0Other times, people will say =E2=80=9Cthis is unacceptable,=E2=80=9D =
and everyone will get together to  reverse the transactions and act like th=
ey never happened. Other times, people will say =E2=80=9Chey let=E2=80=99s =
call the police,=E2=80=9D and perhaps the police will come and arrest the =
=E2=80=9Chacker=E2=80=9D for hacking or market manipulation or whatever. Th=
ere are other possible outcomes. I   wrote yesterday, somewhat fancifully, =
about decentralized autonomous vigilantism as a possible solution to crypto=
 hacks.
Still there does seem to be a developing=C2=A0norm that says =E2=80=9Cif yo=
u hack a decentralized finance protocol and run off with a bunch of money, =
you can keep some of it as a reward for your cleverness, but you have to re=
turn most of it because keeping it all would be mean and perhaps a crime.=
=E2=80=9D The model is a =E2=80=9Cbug bounty,=E2=80=9D though sort of after=
 the fact: If you find a flaw in a protocol=E2=80=99s security, they should=
 pay you a reward for pointing it out, but you should not get to take all t=
heir money.
And so we   talked last week about a guy who did a market manipulation on a=
 DeFi protocol called Mango, taking something like $116 million. The guy=E2=
=80=99s name is Avraham Eisenberg.=C2=A0Here is a post by Chris Brunet roun=
ding up Eisenberg=E2=80=99s alleged Discord posts as he planned this exploi=
t, which include:
=09Eisenberg asks: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m investigating a platform that could=
 maybe lead to a 9 figure payday. Should I do it=E2=80=9D=09Someone in the =
Discord replies =E2=80=9Cprobably =E2=80=A6=C2=A0unles it is highly illegal=
,=E2=80=9D and Eisenberg replies=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAre there rules these days=
=E2=80=9D=09Someone asks =E2=80=9Cis this just one of those oracle manipula=
tooor things to drain LPs,=E2=80=9D and he replies =E2=80=9CSorta. You take=
 a long position. And then you make numba go up.=E2=80=9D

And then Eisenberg himself went on Twitter to issue a =E2=80=9Cstatement on=
 recent events=E2=80=9D that might be up there with Satoshi Nakamoto=E2=80=
=99s Bitcoin white paper as one of the great foundational documents of cryp=
to:

I was involved with a team that operated a highly profitable trading strate=
gy last week.
I believe all of our actions were legal open market actions, using the prot=
ocol as designed, even if the development team did not fully anticipate all=
 the consequences of setting parameters the way they are.
Unfortunately, the exchange this took place on, Mango Markets, became insol=
vent as a result, with the insurance fund being insufficient to cover all l=
iquidations. This led to other users being unable to access their funds.
To remedy the situation, I helped negotiate a settlement agreement with the=
 insurance fund with the goal of making all users whole as soon as possible=
 as well as recapitalizing the exchange.=C2=A0

Mango built a game, and Eisenberg played that game in a highly profitable w=
ay, and as a result he got $116 million and the game ended. But now he will=
 give back some of the money so the game can continue for everyone else.
You can imagine a lot of different background norms working here. =E2=80=9C=
Code is law, anything that happens is fine, and adversarial hardening will =
over time make hacks less likely=E2=80=9D is definitely  a popular take in =
crypto, and maybe it=E2=80=99s fine. But my sense is that if you want crypt=
o to be a big industry, if you want it to be appealing to retail investors =
and large institutions and governments, you will want some other norm. Some=
 norm like =E2=80=9Cif there=E2=80=99s a hack, someone will fix it.=E2=80=
=9D
Sam Bankman-Fried runs the crypto exchange FTX, and his net worth is pretty=
 directly tied to broad retail, institutional and governmental adoption of =
crypto. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Joanna Ossinger reports:

Crypto billionaire Sam Bankman-Fried has outlined a framework for limiting =
the impact of the hacks and exploits plaguing the industry, including cappi=
ng the maximum bounty for attackers at $5 million. =E2=80=A6
Bankman-Fried, co-founder of digital-asset exchange FTX, proposed in a=C2=
=A0blog post=C2=A0what he called a =E2=80=9C5-5 standard=E2=80=9D where hac=
kers keep either 5% of the amount they=E2=80=99ve taken from a protocol or =
$5 million, whichever is smaller.
Other key provisos are that customers must be made whole and that the hacke=
r is acting in =E2=80=9Cgood faith=E2=80=9D and fully intended to cooperate=
 and return most of the assets. In crypto, attackers are sometimes viewed a=
s white-hat hackers who seek to expose vulnerabilities in return for a rewa=
rd rather than to make malicious gains.

Here is the rest of  that post, which consists of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s d=
raft proposals for =E2=80=9Ca set of standards that we as an industry could=
 enact to create clarity and protect customers while waiting for full feder=
al regulatory regimes,=E2=80=9D covering things like sanctions, disclosure,=
 securities regulation, decentralized finance, etc. But I suppose the propo=
sed standardization of hacking rewards is the most interesting part. The id=
ea is to have rewards for cleverness that are=C2=A0generous, but not=C2=A0a=
bsurd, to reward cleverness without making clever hacking the entire point =
of the game.
Of course this doesn=E2=80=99t solve everything. For one thing, how do you =
make hackers follow the industry standards? If a hacker/exploiter/manipulat=
or comes up with a really good trade and steals $500 million, and decides=
=C2=A0not to give back $495 million of it, what do you do? I suppose the an=
swer is =E2=80=9Ccall the police,=E2=80=9D and then you are back to relying=
 on the background norms of the traditional legal system.
Also: What if you find a =E2=80=9Chighly profitable trading strategy=E2=80=
=9D and you =E2=80=9Cbelieve all of [your] actions were legal open market a=
ctions, using the protocol as designed,=E2=80=9D but others disagree and th=
ink you did a hack? =E2=80=9CThe maximum reward for market manipulation is =
$5 million=E2=80=9D is a fine standard, but you still have to have some way=
 to decide what is =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulation=E2=80=9D and what is just c=
lever trading.

