 background-color: #ccc;">
years</a>. Someone buys CDS to bet against (or hedge) the credit risk of a =
company, and someone else sells them that CDS to bet on the credit of that =
company, and then the buyer and the seller separately go to the company and=
 say =E2=80=9Chey if you press this button right here our counterparty will=
 have to give us $50 million and we=E2=80=99ll give you $20 million of it,=
=E2=80=9D and the company is like =E2=80=9Cwho are you? Sure, I guess,=E2=
=80=9D and it is=C2=A0<em>weird</em>. There are intersections between this =
stuff and the real economic world =E2=80=94=C2=A0I think that sometimes it =
is net <em>good=C2=A0</em>for the world, and other times it is net=C2=A0<em=
>bad=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it mostly feels pretty abstract. Some hed=
ge funds are trying to trick each other using finance and that=E2=80=99s ju=
st their business.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are, in the traditional financial system=
,=C2=A0constraints=C2=A0on this sort of cleverness. Obviously one set of co=
nstraints is, like, it is hard to find arbitrages in markets or flaws in co=
ntracts, and the people on the other side are also smart and have good comp=
uters and good lawyers and are trying to trick you too. Still, sometimes yo=
u will find a winning trade.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even so, though, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDYtMTcvYmxvY2tjaGFpbi1jb21wYW55LXMtc21hcn=
QtY29udHJhY3RzLXdlcmUtZHVtYj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDIwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVka=
XVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEwMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBh=
aWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf6466e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  there are =
a lot of external constraints</a>, constraints of laws and norms. If you fi=
nd a flaw in a contract that says your counterparty has to pay you $50 mill=
ion, she might say no. And you might go to court over it, and point to the =
language that says she has to pay you $50 million, and the judge might say =
=E2=80=9Cwhat, no, this is stupid, it can=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0<em>meant=C2=
=A0</em>that, get out of here.=E2=80=9D The judge will refer to vague ideas=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0equity, the intent of the parties, the covenant of good fai=
th and fair dealing =E2=80=94=C2=A0to reject your clever reading of the con=
tract.=C2=A0And then you won=E2=80=99t get your $50 million. There is some =
amount of cleverness that is=C2=A0<em>too </em>clever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or if you find some really clever market-struc=
ture trick, some button that you can push to reliably make money on every t=
rade, a regulator might=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTItMDQvdHJ5aW5nLXRvLWJ1eS1zdHVmZi15b3Utd2FudC1pcy1ub3QtbWF=
uaXB1bGF0aW9uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfbf7934f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">show up and accuse you</=
a> of =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulation.=E2=80=9D That is a somewhat ill-defined=
 concept, but if you are reliably making money on every trade by being clev=
erer than your counterparties, there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that you are=
 guilty of it. (And in=C2=A0fact the US Securities and Exchange Commission =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTYvdGhlL=
XNlYy1oYXMtYmlnLXBsYW5zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09=
ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ24=
9bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4c7fdb0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  seems to think=
</a> that causing a =E2=80=9Cmanufactured default=E2=80=9D in CDS =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0asking a company to push a button=C2=A0to make your CDS counterparty =
pay you =E2=80=94=C2=A0is illegal market manipulation.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or: About a decade ago, some electricity trade=
rs at JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. read the rule book of the electricity market=
 really closely and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWFsYnJlYWtlci5jb20vMjAxMy8wNy9lbGVjdHJpY2l0e=
S1tYXJrZXQtcnVsZXMtd2VyZS1ub3QtYS13b3J0aHktb3Bwb25lbnQtZm9yLWpwbW9yZ2Fucy1i=
cmFpbnBvd2Vy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd8d8d493" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> noticed that the r=
ules would reward them</a> for insanely uneconomic activity. They did this =
insanely uneconomic activity, and were richly rewarded. And then they were =
even more richly fined by regulators. I once <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDYtMTcvYmxvY2tjaGFpbi1jb21wYW55LXMtc21hcnQ=
tY29udHJhY3RzLXdlcmUtZHVtYj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDIwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEwMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCcf6466e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote about=
 this case</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan read the rules carefully =
and greedily, and exploited the rules. It did this openly and honestly, in =
ways that were ridiculous but=C2=A0explicitly allowed by the rules. The Fed=
eral Energy Regulatory Commission fined it $410 million for doing this, and=
 JPMorgan meekly paid up. What JPMorgan did was explicitly=C2=A0<em>allowed=
 by the rules</em>, but that doesn't mean that it was=C2=A0<em>allowed</em>=
. Just because rules are dumb and you are smart, that doesn't always mean t=
hat you get to take advantage of them.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some very high level of generality, there a=
re the explicit rules =E2=80=94=C2=A0the words of the contract, the mechani=
sms of the stock exchange, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then there is a backgrou=
nd set of fairness norms. And if you find a way to make a ton of money with=
 a too-clever reading of the explicit rules, the background fairness norms =
will kick into gear and you will get in trouble. Following the rules is goo=
d, but following the rules to absurd places is bad, perhaps a crime.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In crypto =E2=80=A6=C2=A0yeesh. In crypto, exp=
licit rules are very popular, and are often coded into computer programs. T=
he rules of a decentralized finance market will be embedded in open-source =
smart contracts, and you can read them, and if you find a clever way to exp=
loit them =E2=80=94=C2=A0to =E2=80=9Chack=E2=80=9D the smart contract, or t=
o =E2=80=9Cmanipulate=E2=80=9D the market, to use loaded, traditional terms=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you can do that, quickly and efficiently and at scale.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But crypto is also very=C2=A0<em>young</em>, a=
s an industry, which means two things:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">All these smart contracts were writte=
n 20 minutes ago, they do not have many years of testing, and some of them =
will have big flaws that someone can exploit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">There is not long-standing agreement on some set of background =
norms about what to do when that happens.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so sometimes there will be a =E2=80=9Chack=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cexploit=E2=80=9D in crypto and people will say =E2=80=
=9Chey that=E2=80=99s great, the contract worked as written, you=E2=80=99re=
 not allowed to complain.=E2=80=9D (Thus the scare quotes around =E2=80=9Ch=
ack=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cexploit=E2=80=9D: Some people will deny that thos=
e loaded=C2=A0terms apply.)=C2=A0Other times, people will say =E2=80=9Cthis=
 is unacceptable,=E2=80=9D and everyone will get together to <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Z2VtaW5pLmNvbS9jcnlwdG9wZWRpYS90aGUtZGFvLWhhY2stbWFrZXJkYW8/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB04e54a55" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> reverse the transactions and act like they n=
ever happened</a>. Other times, people will say =E2=80=9Chey let=E2=80=99s =
call the police,=E2=80=9D and perhaps the police will come and arrest the =
=E2=80=9Chacker=E2=80=9D for hacking or market manipulation or whatever. Th=
ere are other possible outcomes. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTkvbGV2ZXJhZ2VkLWJ1eW91dHMtbG9zZS1zb21lLWxldmVyY=
WdlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJj=
ZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeae99963" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote yesterday</a>, somewhat fanc=
ifully, about decentralized autonomous vigilantism as a possible solution t=
o crypto hacks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there does seem to be a developing=C2=A0=
norm that says =E2=80=9Cif you hack a decentralized finance protocol and ru=
n off with a bunch of money, you can keep some of it as a reward for your c=
leverness, but you have to return most of it because keeping it all would b=
e mean and perhaps a crime.=E2=80=9D The model is a =E2=80=9Cbug bounty,=E2=
=80=9D though sort of after the fact: If you find a flaw in a protocol=E2=
=80=99s security, they should pay you a reward for pointing it out, but you=
 should not get to take all their money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTIvZGVmaS1kaXNjb3ZlcnMtbmV3LW1hcmtldC1tYW5pc=
HVsYXRpb25zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
mZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2a246bd8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked last week</a> about=
 a guy who did a market manipulation on a DeFi protocol called Mango, takin=
g something like $116 million. The guy=E2=80=99s name is Avraham Eisenberg.=
=C2=A0Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2943=
9806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly9rYXJsc3RhY2suc3Vic3RhY2suY29tL3AvZXhjbHVzaXZlLXRoZS1=
tYW4td2hvLW1heS1oYXZlLW1pbGtlZA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc0d8e55d" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
a post by Chris Brunet</a> rounding up Eisenberg=E2=80=99s alleged Discord =
posts as he planned this exploit, which include:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eisenberg asks: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m i=
nvestigating a platform that could maybe lead to a 9 figure payday. Should =
I do it=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Someone in the Di=
scord replies =E2=80=9Cprobably =E2=80=A6=C2=A0unles it is highly illegal,=
=E2=80=9D and Eisenberg replies=C2=A0=E2=80=9CAre there rules these days=E2=
=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Someone asks =E2=80=9Cis th=
is just one of those oracle manipulatooor things to drain LPs,=E2=80=9D and=
 he replies =E2=80=9CSorta. You take a long position. And then you make num=
ba go up.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then Eisenberg himself went on Twitter to =
issue a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
9439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9hdmlfZWlzZW4vc3RhdHVzLzE1ODEzMjYx=
OTcyNDExODAxNjA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB71478961" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">statement on rec=
ent events</a>=E2=80=9D that might be up there with Satoshi Nakamoto=E2=80=
=99s Bitcoin white paper as one of the great foundational documents of cryp=
to:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I was involved with a team that operated a hig=
hly profitable trading strategy last week.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I believe all of our actions were legal open m=
arket actions, using the protocol as designed, even if the development team=
 did not fully anticipate all the consequences of setting parameters the wa=
y they are.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unfortunately, the exchange this took place on=
, Mango Markets, became insolvent as a result, with the insurance fund bein=
g insufficient to cover all liquidations. This led to other users being una=
ble to access their funds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To remedy the situation, I helped negotiate a =
settlement agreement with the insurance fund with the goal of making all us=
ers whole as soon as possible as well as recapitalizing the exchange.=C2=A0=
</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mango built a game, and Eisenberg played that =
game in a highly profitable way, and as a result he got $116 million and th=
e game ended. But now he will give back some of the money so the game can c=
ontinue for everyone else.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can imagine a lot of different background =
norms working here. =E2=80=9CCode is law, anything that happens is fine, an=
d adversarial hardening will over time make hacks less likely=E2=80=9D is d=
efinitely <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806=
.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly9taWxreWVnZ3MuY29tLz9wPTYx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa5941=
9b9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> a popular take in crypto</a>, and maybe it=E2=80=99s fine. Bu=
t my sense is that if you want crypto to be a big industry, if you want it =
to be appealing to retail investors and large institutions and governments,=
 you will want some other norm. Some norm like =E2=80=9Cif there=E2=80=99s =
a hack, someone will fix it.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sam Bankman-Fried runs the crypto exchange FTX=
, and his net worth is pretty directly tied to broad retail, institutional =
and governmental adoption of crypto. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMjAvYmlsbGlvbmFpcmUtYmFua21hbi1=
mcmllZC10cmllcy10by1maXgtY3J5cHRvLXMtaGFja2luZy1wcm9ibGVtP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMj=
AyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0b=
V90ZXJtPTIyMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
c35bc2ed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">  Joanna Ossinger reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto billionaire Sam Bankman-Fried has outli=
ned a framework for limiting the impact of the hacks and exploits plaguing =
the industry, including capping the maximum bounty for attackers at $5 mill=
ion. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bankman-Fried, co-founder of digital-asset exc=
hange FTX, proposed in a=C2=A0blog post=C2=A0what he called a =E2=80=9C5-5 =
standard=E2=80=9D where hackers keep either 5% of the amount they=E2=80=99v=
e taken from a protocol or $5 million, whichever is smaller.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Other key provisos are that customers must be =
made whole and that the hacker is acting in =E2=80=9Cgood faith=E2=80=9D an=
d fully intended to cooperate and return most of the assets. In crypto, att=
ackers are sometimes viewed as white-hat hackers who seek to expose vulnera=
bilities in return for a reward rather than to make malicious gains.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the rest of <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnR4cG9saWN5=
LmNvbS9wb3N0cy9wb3NzaWJsZS1kaWdpdGFsLWFzc2V0LWluZHVzdHJ5LXN0YW5kYXJkcw/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93897ac9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> that post</a>, which consists of Ba=
nkman-Fried=E2=80=99s draft proposals for =E2=80=9Ca set of standards that =
we as an industry could enact to create clarity and protect customers while=
 waiting for full federal regulatory regimes,=E2=80=9D covering things like=
 sanctions, disclosure, securities regulation, decentralized finance, etc. =
But I suppose the proposed standardization of hacking rewards is the most i=
nteresting part. The idea is to have rewards for cleverness that are=C2=A0<=
em>generous</em>, but not=C2=A0<em>absurd</em>, to reward cleverness withou=
t making clever hacking the entire point of the game.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course this doesn=E2=80=99t solve everythin=
g. For one thing, how do you make hackers follow the industry standards? If=
 a hacker/exploiter/manipulator comes up with a really good trade and steal=
s $500 million, and decides=C2=A0<em>not </em>to give back $495 million of =
it, what do you do? I suppose the answer is =E2=80=9Ccall the police,=E2=80=
=9D and then you are back to relying on the background norms of the traditi=
onal legal system.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also: What if you find a =E2=80=9Chighly profi=
table trading strategy=E2=80=9D and you =E2=80=9Cbelieve all of [your] acti=
ons were legal open market actions, using the protocol as designed,=E2=80=
=9D but others disagree and think you did a hack? =E2=80=9CThe maximum rewa=
rd for market manipulation is $5 million=E2=80=9D is a fine standard, but y=
ou still have to have some way to decide what is =E2=80=9Cmarket manipulati=
on=E2=80=9D and what is just clever trading.</p>
