 out there are bots on Twitter=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then talking up the =
value of Twitter this week would make it even funnier. So you never know. B=
ut, probably, closing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is he overpaying? Leaving aside all of the leg=
al wrangling, Musk=E2=80=99s deal for Twitter is a strange bit of merger=C2=
=A0<em>economics</em>. You could tell a story that goes something like:=C2=
=A0</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Twitter is worth about $20 billion.<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When Musk buys it and spruces it =
up, it will be worth $200 billion, an order of magnitude more, in the same =
ballpark as Meta Platforms Inc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Th=
ere is absolutely no way that Twitter can make itself worth more than $20 b=
illion without Musk. Whatever Musk will do to make Twitter worth $200 billi=
on is something that only he could do; Twitter cannot implement his plan, o=
r some other plan, or hire better executives, or restructure itself, or do =
anything else on its own that will create anything like the value he can.</=
li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>merger stories li=
ke that, where the buyer has some plausible way to extract significant syne=
rgies from the target. You combine the target=E2=80=99s widget business wit=
h the buyer=E2=80=99s sprocket business and you can cross-sell widget/sproc=
ket combinations at a huge premium, etc. The target is worth $20 billion on=
 its own, but $30 billion combined with the buyer, and only the buyer can c=
reate that combination.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Musk is not a big corporation doing a stra=
tegic deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0he=E2=80=99s a guy =E2=80=94=C2=A0and there are n=
o obvious synergies between Twitter and his other businesses (cars, rockets=
, tunnels, brain implants). On the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGlua3MuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL3N0b3JpZXMvUkswV00xR0pDRDIxP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZ=
WRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAyMCZ1dG1fY2Ft=
cGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcb377da1" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Tesla e=
arnings call</a>, Musk was asked =E2=80=9CWith your pending acquisition of =
Twitter and your stakes in SpaceX and Neuralink and Tesla, how much would t=
he combined companies benefit from operating under a single super structure=
, if at all, like a Google Alphabet?=E2=80=9D And he replied =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s not clear to me what the overlap is. It=E2=80=99s not 0, but it=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=A0I think we=E2=80=99re reaching.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also Musk has given <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5j=
b20vMjAyMi8wNS8wNi90ZWNobm9sb2d5L2Vsb24tbXVzay10d2l0dGVyLXBpdGNoLWRlY2suaHR=
tbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd1109d4c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> some indication</a> of his =
plans for Twitter, and there is no=C2=A0<em>obvious=C2=A0</em>roadmap to $2=
00 billion. It=E2=80=99s all stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0charge for some features,=
 try to get more users =E2=80=94=C2=A0that Twitter=E2=80=99s existing manag=
ement could have thought of, and probably did.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Musk, in this story, has some magic power:=
 He can create tens of billions of dollars of market value by waving a magi=
c wand, in a way that no ordinary mortal can replicate or even understand. =
I, uh, I guess I almost believe that? =E2=80=9CThe way finance works now is=
 that things are valuable not based on their cash flows but on their proxim=
ity to Elon Musk,=E2=80=9D I have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMTAvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXR3ZWV0cy1ncmVhdC1uZXdzLWZvci1iaX=
Rjb2luLWJhZC1uZXdzLWZvci1lY29uLW1ham9ycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDIwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGR=
iZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEwMjAm=
dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf93ecd32" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  often written</a>. I call this the Elon Markets Hypothesis. It seems to b=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMDMvZXZ=
lcnlvbmUtd2FudGVkLXRvLWJ1eS10d2l0dGVyLXdpdGgtZWxvbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDIwMjJfTU=
9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVyb=
T0yMjEwMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91e344b=
e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  what motivated his co-investors</a> to join him in the Twitt=
er deal. Musk creates value out of thin air. Twitter is bad now, but it has=
 incredible potential, and only Musk can unlock it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a typical strategic merger there will be so=
me negotiation over the allocation of synergies. The target is worth $20 bi=
llion on its own, it will be worth $30 billion if the buyer buys it, and th=
e target will want to get some of that $10 billion for its own shareholders=
. That $10 billion is created by the combination; neither the buyer nor the=
 target can get it on their own. If the buyer pays $25 billion for the targ=
et, it isn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Coverpaying=E2=80=9D; it=E2=80=99s sharing the=
 synergies.=C2=A0In a rough sense I suppose that happened here. Twitter is =
worth $20 billion on its own, and $200 billion with Musk=E2=80=99s magic. M=
ost of the value comes from his magic, but he does need=C2=A0<em>Twitter=C2=
=A0</em>to do the magic on. He=E2=80=99s paying more than it=E2=80=99s wort=
h now, but less than it=E2=80=99s worth=C2=A0<em>to him</em>.</p>
