der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Tracy Alloway on insti=
tutional investors trading short-dated options</a>, quoting Charlie McEllig=
ott, a strategist at Nomura Securities International Inc.:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYOLOing into 0 and 1 Days-Til-Expirat=
ion (DTE) options has now been =E2=80=98institutionalized=E2=80=99 by vol t=
raders at many of the largest funds on the Street,=E2=80=9D McElligott wrot=
e in a note to clients. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not about retail-alone playin=
g this game anymore.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe have seen witnessed some absolutel=
y biblical usage of 0DTE and 1DTE options, and it=E2=80=99s acting like jet=
 fuel being dumped on the already out of control =E2=80=98macro=E2=80=99 fi=
re occurring into persistent =E2=80=98negative gamma=E2=80=99 momentum over=
shoot flows,=E2=80=9D he added. =E2=80=9CUsing the certainty of dealer hedg=
ing flows that their orders create to then amplify and =E2=80=98juice=E2=80=
=99 the intended directional market move =E2=80=A6 before closing-out posit=
ions mere hours later by end of day.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Biblical jet fuel is juicing the flows of fire=
! Love it. More, please:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMost critically as it rel=
ates to the outrageous ranges and swings this past week in US equities and =
into the upcoming expiration, it is the staggering amount of (negative) fro=
nt-delta into Friday=E2=80=99s [options expiry] that has then needed to be =
traded on the approach, which is then acting as further shadow-convexity in=
 the market,=E2=80=9D he says.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ahh so good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look. Retail investors on Reddit have been say=
ing for years that there is a viable trading strategy that goes like this:<=
/p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You buy short-dated out-of-the-money =
call options on a stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This forc=
es options dealers to buy that stock to hedge the options.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This pushes the stock up.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">As the stock goes up, the dealers need to buy even=C2=A0<e=
m>more </em>of the stock to remain properly hedged.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">This pushes the stock up more.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">As the stock goes up, your call options are more valuable.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Congratulations, you have created a=
 self-fulfilling trade. You can=E2=80=99t lose.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When I first heard this theory, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDItMjYvcmVkZGl0LXBvc3RlcnM=
tcGljay10aGUtc3RvY2tzLW5vdz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDIwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEwMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3d19886b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I was skept=
ical</a>. Yes, right, at some level this is a correct description of how de=
alers hedge call options: They buy some stock to hedge options that they se=
ll, and then buy more stock as the price goes up. But there is a lot of oth=
er stuff going on in the market, and it seems implausible that retail inves=
tors buying stock options would be able to push around the price of a big l=
iquid stock like Tesla Inc. And the effect of dealer hedging goes both ways=
: If the stock goes=C2=A0<em>down</em>, dealers will sell some of their sto=
ck to remain properly hedged, which will push it down more. You are not get=
ting a free lunch. The idea that this would just=C2=A0<em>work</em>, as a s=
elf-fulfilling automatic money maker, seemed absurd.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, it=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>absurd, but a=
fter January 2021 I am more open to the possibility that it=C2=A0<em>happen=
s</em>. Did retail investors buy a ton of short-dated out-of-the-money call=
 options on GameStop Corp., <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/29439806.290503/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
